{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523401"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13893"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13893"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.35,0.07,0.06,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6512"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49036"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6512"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13893"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34057"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"868"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19142"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44555"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49036"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 85-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of nausea, vomiting, and progressive abdominal distension. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended and tympanic, with a palpable mass in the right lower quadrant. Bowel sounds are high-pitched and tinkling. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her small bowel obstruction based on this image?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adhesions","Spigelian hernia","Neuroendocrine tumour","Gallstone ileus","Closed loop obstruction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT image shows a loop of small bowel herniating through the anterio-lateral abdominal wall, consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003ESpigelian hernia\u003C/strong\u003E (Image). Spigelian hernias are rare ventral hernias that occur at the lateral edge of the rectus abdominis muscle, below the arcuate line. They can be difficult to diagnose clinically due to their location and often require imaging for confirmation. In this case, the hernia is causing a small bowel obstruction, which explains the patient\u0027s symptoms of nausea, vomiting, and abdominal distension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdhesions\u003C/strong\u003E are a common cause of small bowel obstruction, especially in patients with a history of abdominal surgery. However, the CT image clearly shows a hernia as the cause of obstruction, rather than adhesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eneuroendocrine tumour\u003C/strong\u003E of the small bowel could potentially cause obstruction, but it would appear as a mass within the bowel lumen or wall, not as a hernia through the abdominal wall as seen in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallstone ileus\u003C/strong\u003E is an uncommon cause of small bowel obstruction, typically seen in elderly patients. It occurs when a large gallstone erodes through the gallbladder wall into the small bowel, causing a mechanical obstruction. The CT would show pneumobilia, a dilated small bowel, and an ectopic gallstone, none of which are present in this image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eclosed loop obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when a segment of bowel is obstructed at two points along its course, often due to adhesions or internal herniation. While this can be a serious cause of small bowel obstruction, the CT image clearly shows an external hernia as the cause, not a closed loop within the abdominal cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spigelian hernias are rare lateral abdominal wall hernias that can cause small bowel obstruction.","CT imaging is the gold standard for diagnosing Spigelian hernias.","Small bowel obstruction in elderly patients should prompt consideration of less common causes such as abdominal wall hernias."],"references":["Clark C, Kelly M, Palamuthisingam P. Spigelian hernia: a multi-site review of oeprative outcomes of surgical repair in the adult population. Hernia. 2024;28:537-546. Available at:   https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10029-023-02946-1","Mittal T, Kumar V, Sharma A, et al. Diagnosis and management of Spihelian hernia: A review of literature and our experience. Journal of Minical Access Surgery. 2008;4(4):95-98. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19547696/","Vetter C, Lowe K.  A Case of an incision spigelian-type hernia.Vetter CJ, Lowe K. A Case of an Incisional Spigelian-Type Hernia. ACS Case Reviews in Surgery. 2024;4(5):85-87. Available at: https://www.facs.org/media/sckl1rge/18-vetter-incisional-spigelian-type-hernia.pdf","Jones J, Bell D, Amer M, et al. Small  bowel obstruction. Reference article. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/small-bowel-obstruction"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34057"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13893"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20833"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20884"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20833"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wURJDsV92l5rlmJcukrJst1K95zHIu.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wURJDsV92l5rlmJcukrJst1K95zHIu.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":515,"height":751}},{"type":"media","id":"20884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20884"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/o4N0igYv60cQ1J5Sean8WmJGHtn3bJ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/o4N0igYv60cQ1J5Sean8WmJGHtn3bJ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":515,"height":751}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34057"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T16:36:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-13T22:42:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6512"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49036"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":